author: @MR-op3mo
comment: I don't mind surveillance, I understand how someone could feel more secure under surveillance, especially if you trust your local government and authorities and if there are strict rules as to how that information is used (for security mainly).  It makes me feel more secure walking around at night, and young people who are wandering about early in the morning...cameras and surveillance could help to ensure security, again this information should have strict rules as to usage!  But why not?  Best not to be afraid, but to see how we can use this technology to increase security (no more danger for young girls walking home alone after a party, no more young boys being stabbed on the corners, no more drugs being sold to the young, no more gangs that are able to gang up on individuals and steal, kill and even rape.  No more bike thieves, no more break-ins, no more kidnappings, no more children being taken and killed...I don't know, I can see all sorts of good things that can be used with our surveillance data.  We should move from fear, to how our data can be used to keep us and our children safer, and how we can ensure that our data is not used against us, and I believe most governments want the same thing.

author: @OCinTexile
comment: Huh??  I haven't watched the video, but the title's question is insane.  China is STILL, as it has been for more than 70 years, a Communist Party dictatorship and surveillance of its citizenry to ensure they comply with government diktat has, along with the constant threat of state terror against its citizens, ALWAYS been the method used to maintain the Party's stranglehold over the "willing" citizenry.  It should be well known to all that the people of China have no inviolable rights.  The government can and does do whatever it feels necessary to its people.  They enforce "willingness" and there is an absolute lack of the right to privacy.  By constant surveillance citizens of China can be arrested and held without charge, submitted to trials whose outcome against them is guaranteed, disappear into internal Chinese gulag-style labor camps or be summarily executed, and their "property" can be searched and/or confiscated at the whim of government officials - these have paperwork to give everything the appearance of veracity and legitimate authority, but the Party controls all aspects of government, executive, legislative and judicial.  There is no rule of law in China - the Party is the law.  Remember, the people have NO freedom of speech, religion, press, association, due process, nor right to a fair trial in any matter and never have in the past 72 years since the revolution (except for a very short period in 1989 when Party control loosened for a time before the brutal crackdown in Tiananmen Square restored its absolute control), and certainly do NOT have the right to not be under constant surveillance,  even in their own homes.  Saying they are willing participants is ludicrous when they have no choice.  They in fact have no positive freedoms or rights at all.  The country's government is thoroughly corrupt, dishonest and while it may lack Mao's deranged brutality, maintains the same level of control by more subtle but equally terrifying means as ever.  The only thing that's changed in China regarding surveillance is that new technology has allowed it to become much more powerful, intrusive and all-pervasive, impacting every aspect of Chinese life, very much in the way Big Brother is depicted in Orwell's 1984.  If China is the way of the future, then the future really will be a very bleak place.  All free peoples should be doing everything they can to ensure that China's pathologies do not spread beyond its borders, and, as far as is possible (not much sadly), attempt to minimize the damage caused by all-pervasive surveillance in China itself.

author: @eddielao7568
comment: You said that you were not able to verify many details of sidik's story, but you did not present other views. Your presentation is biased against China. I am Chinese and i believe most Chinese like what the government is doing. As long as you don't do anything illegal or immoral, you have no problem that the government knows where you have been, what you have done, or what you like or dislike. Instead you feel safer in the street because criminals know that they will be caught and are less likely to do anything to you publicly. I have been to Uramqi and there are checkpoints everywhere. And these checkpoints make me feel safe. If the police discover a wanted criminal, shouldn't they arrest him immediately. Covering the head of a suspect during arrest is a way to protect the suspect and is practiced by some western countries. What is wrong with that? Criticizing the government will not land you in jail because you can see people doing that over the internet. It's when you criticize the government with the intention to subvert it or create social unrest that will be penalized. China does have some censorship on sensitive political issues, but over 90 percent of the people supports the government and are satisfied with what the government is doing. That's much better than most, if not all, western countries.

author: @andreashauschild7757
comment: I live in China, now for 13 years. And I can tell you that unless you do something against the rules you will never be bothered by this. But you will enjoy the benefits. The amount of for instance people just dumping their garbage outside just because they are to lazy to walk the 50 meters to the collection station has dropped to 0 in our complex after they added cameras. Now you can walk through the complex and not see or smell garbage. A plus. Also me or my wife can walk in the city, a gigantic city without fearing any violent crime, even late at night. Its not even on our mind. Overall the monitoring in my opinion has lead to a almost entire society without violent daily crime. You still have stuff happening when people get angry or drunk, but that is a small percentage. I rather not have to worry about getting mugged or raped then have to worry about the government looking over my shoulder.

author: @Buckzoo2030
comment: Surveillance is a loaded word.  Our smartphones that monitor everything we do is also a surveillance system.  With AI and smart door bell and thermostat, tech companies also know when we are home and probably which room you are in.  In China, on top of all that, the government is  monitoring you in public space too.  In principle, the government can demand tech companies streaming them users data and still have a very good idea what are you doing milliseconds  by milliseconds.  So, what’s the fuzz? And why the Chinese government want you to know they are watching you?  Is the smartphone system we have that much better?  It’s likely a Yes because of privacy laws.   For a country that’s doesn’t have much privacy culture, privacy may not be treated  as important as laws against theft or jaywalking,  thus no laws guarding privacy?   Could this be a cultural issue?  If so, people in China may not find surveillance an intrusion but rather a protection shield for them.  It’s all our mind (brain), could it be.  Those who are raised in the west that values privacy will always find it a surveillance system, those who are raised in China may think otherwise.

author: @jameswhaling7493
comment: Another reason for the Chinese to take privacy a little differently from the west is because of number of people per unit area, that is: population density. In China, and in many Asian countries in general (eg: India), the mean distance between people is magnitudes smaller than that in the west. People were born into such environment. The subtle effect of which is that it becomes natural for them not minding (or not caring) watchful eyes of other people. It just becomes a way of life. So, they are not as self-conscious about living with less privacy than expected in the west.

author: @dr.bigface8895
comment: I’m going to be blunt, but I’m pretty sure this type of video is literally just here to try to scare us. And I’m gonna break this whole thing down. I am not a tech expert or a coder or developer but I do know that chatGPT is closed source and deepseek is open source so comparing the threat levels of the two is completely irrelevant. Honestly, you should be more scared of ChatGPT because you can’t run that locally and you can’t host it through another service. But with deep seek, if you have the hardware to run it, then you can run it and you can fine tune it and you can do whatever you want with it. And if you can’t run it, then there’s gotta be a service that hosts it on their own server. I’m pretty sure you can get an API to use it for much cheaper than ChatGPT with fireworks and that’s an American company. I totally understand being scared to use it through the website or the official API and I am wary of that too. But other than that, it’s just a model. They’re only doing this much fear mongering about the China stuff because openAI doesn’t want to lose the top spot. But if openAI were Chinese, you guys would’ve been breaking a sweat years ago. Honestly, you should be more scared of them than you are deepSeek because they are stealing your data and you can’t use their model and prohibit it very well. I don’t mean to offend anyone, but we really need to stop looking at really good technology with the most permissive licenses and complaining about politics instead of being grateful that there is technology that is not locked behind a $200 pay wall.
